{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> νῶτον</b>, τό, <br /> or <b>νῶτος</b>, ὁ, <i>plural</i> always νῶτα, τά in early writers (οἱ νῶτοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.3Ki.7.19(33))\">LXX</a>]: the gender of thesg. is undetermined in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus and 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus; _neuter_ in 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.28, 4.83, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Cyclops” 237, 643, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 289, “Pax” 747, 4th c.BC: Antiphanes Comicus 132.6 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], and always in <i>Attic dialect</i> <i>accusative</i> to [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Phrynichus Atticista 257, etc.: _accusative_ νῶτον\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>] is <i>masculine</i> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “προρρητικόν” 2.30, 40, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “de Equitandi ratione” 3.3 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] (as cited by Hdn.Gr.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.215), 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 512b17, 544a6, 4th c.BC: Ephorus Historicus 224J. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>back,</b> both cf men and animals: <i>singular</i>, of a man, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.147, 13.289, etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of a boar, φρίσσεινῶτον[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 473; ν... ὄϊος καὶ πίονος αἰγός 9.207 \">Refs</a>]; of horses, ἐπὶ νῶτον ἐῗσαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2.765 \">Refs</a>]; of an eagle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.9 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>plural</i> frequently used in Poets in sense of <i>singular</i>, δράκων ἐπὶ νῶτα δαφοινός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.308, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.225, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: sometimes in <i>Epic dialect</i> of the <b>chine</b> of an animal served as food, νῶτα βοὸς.. πίονα[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 4.65; νώτοισιν δ᾽ Ὀδυσῆα διηνεκέεσσι γέραιρεν 14.437, compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.321 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of men in battle, τὰ νῶτα ἐντρέψαι to turn <b>the back,</b> i.e. flee, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.211 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νῶτον ἐπιστρέψαι[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Oracle texts [prev. work] 141; σν μὴ δῷς ν. μηδενί “PTeb.” 21.8 (2nd c.BC) \">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>]; δοτέον τὰ ν. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.787f; δεῖξαι νῶτα [prev. author] “Marc.” 12 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>] (this phrase also of the winner in a race, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Anthologia Graeca” 9.557 (Antip. Thess.)); πίπτειν ἐπὶ νώτῳ 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 91 (Lyric poetry) \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; κατὰ νώτου in <b>rear,</b> κατὰ νώτου γενέσθαι τινός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.9, 10 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ στρατόπεδον κατὰ ν. λαβεῖν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 75; κατὰ ν. βοηθεῖν 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.62, etc.; κατὰ νῶτα 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 22.84 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>back</b> of the finger, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.AD: Procopius Caesariensis Historicus Gaz. “Ecphr.” 168.11. \">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <i>metaphorically</i>, <b>any wide surface,</b> especially of the sea, ἐπ᾽ εὐρέα νῶτα θαλάσσης [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.159, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.142, compare 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 762; ἐν νώτοισι ποντίας ἁλός 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 129; πόντου 'πὶ νώτοις [prev. work] 774 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also of the land, σχίζε ν. γᾶς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.228, compare 26; χθονὸς ν. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Taurica” 46 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of the sky, ἀστεροειδέα ν. αἰθέρος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “fragment” 114a p. 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Thesmophoriazusae” 1067 (Lyric poetry); ἐπὶ τῷ τοῦ οὐρανοῦ ν. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 247c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but ἕσπερα ν. the <b>evening,</b> i.e. <b>western, sky,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 731 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>ridge</b> of a hill or rock, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.87, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 128 (Lyric poetry) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a tomb, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Hel.” 842, etc. \">Refs</a>]; of a chariot, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Tr.” 572 (_anapaest meter_) \">Refs</a>]; of a saw, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Anthologia Graeca” 6.204 (1st c.AD: Leonidas Alexandrinus Epigrammaticus). \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> <b>nave</b> of a wheel, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX [prev. cited] \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> <b>back</b> of a page, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 15.624; τὰ κατὰ νώτου “POxy.” 1725.9 (3rd c.AD). (Perh. cf. Latin νᾰτε ¯ ς.) \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G3577","accentedUnicode":"νῶτον","shortDef":"- the back","mediumDef":"the back of men or animals","stepGloss":"back","stepTransliteration":"nōton","count":1,"_es_Definition":"espalda","_zh_tw_Definition":"背部 (羅 11:10)","_zh_Definition":"背部 (罗 11:10)","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"lưng.","_zh_tw_Gloss":"腰","_es_Gloss":"espalda","_zh_Gloss":"腰"}]}